  "original_title": "Sri Lanka bond markets inactive ahead of auction, guidance peg weakens",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "Sri Lanka bond markets inactive ahead of auction, guidance peg weakens",
      "author": "",
      "body_lines": [
        "ECONOMYNEXT \u2013 Sri Lanka\u2019s bonds markets were dead ahead of bond auction, while a guidance peg for interbank spot transactions weakened by one rupee to 361.35 to the US dollars.",
        "Commercial banks were offering dollars for telegraphic transfers at rates between 368.35 and 370.00 for small transactions on July 11.",
        "Banks offered to buy inward remittances at 358.50 -360.00 rupees.",
        "Bond markets were inactive after a steep rise in rates last Wednesday followed by a smaller 100 basis rate hike.",
        "\u201cNo bonds or bills quoted as at this moment,\u201d a dealer said.",
        "\u201cThere is a bond auction and all investors are waiting for that.\u201d",
        "On July 09, protesters in Sri Lanka gathered in Colombo, pressuring both President Gotabaya Rajapaksa and the Prime Minister Ranil Wickremesinghe to resign from their posts.",
        "President Rjapaksa has announced that, he will be resigning from the post on July 13.",
        "The political uncertainty was also weighing on the market, dealers said. A train fare hike set for Monday has been delayed. (Colombo/July11/2022)"
      ],
